%I A396669 #11 Jun 08 2026 17:24:23
%S A396669 0,0,0,73,25209,4457390
%N A396669 Number of relations on an n-set whose minimum-deletion-to-transitivity equals two.
%C A396669 a(n) counts binary relations R on {1,...,n} such that R is not transitive, no single-pair deletion from R yields a transitive relation, but there exist two ordered pairs p, q in R with R \ {p, q} transitive. That is, the minimum number of single-pair deletions required to make R transitive equals 2.
%C A396669 Companion to A395919, which counts relations requiring exactly two deletions.
%e A396669 For n = 3, the directed 3-cycle R = {(1,2), (2,3), (3,1)} is the smallest example by cardinality. R is not transitive: (1,2) and (2,3) are in R but (1,3) is not; similarly (2,3),(3,1) require (2,1) and (3,1),(1,2) require (3,2). Deleting any single ordered pair leaves two pairs that still violate transitivity e.g., removing (1,2) leaves {(2,3),(3,1)}, which requires (2,1). Deleting any two ordered pairs leaves a single pair, which is trivially transitive. Hence the minimum-deletion-to-transitivity equals 2. The reverse 3-cycle {(1,3),(3,2),(2,1)} is the other obvious example; the remaining 71 relations on {1,2,3} arise from extensions of such cores with reflexive pairs and additional violating arcs.
%Y A396669 Cf. A396664, A395083.
